federal building. Returning to an America ripped apart by a war that, in their view, they were not allowed to win, a small but driven group of veterans, active-duty personnel, and civilian supporters concluded that waging war on their own country was justified. They unified people from a variety of militant groups, including Klansmen, neo-Nazis, skinheads, radical tax protestors, and white separatists. The white power movement operated with discipline and clarity, undertaking assassinations, mercenary soldiering, armed robbery, counterfeiting, and weapons trafficking. Its command structure gave women a prominent place in brokering intergroup alliances and giving birth to future recruits. Belew’s disturbing history reveals how war cannot be contained in time and space. In its wake, grievances intensify and violence becomes a logical course of action for some. Bring the War Home argues for awareness of the heightened potential for paramilitarism in a present defined by ongoing war.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aParamilitary forceszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aVietnam War, 1961-1975xVeteranszUnited States. 0aWhite supremacy movementszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh  aAryan Nations.  aGreensboro shooting.  aKu Klux Klan.  aLouis Beam.  aOklahoma City bombing.  aRichard Butler.  aRuby Ridge.  aTimothy McVeigh.  aVietnam War.  aWaco.  aanticommunism.  adomestic terrorism.  aleaderless resistance.  amercenaries.  amilitia movement.  aparamilitarism.  aracism.  aseparatism.  athe Order.  awhite power movement.  awhite supremacy.  awhite women.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060662140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067498494340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn